Equine morbillivirus, bats - Papua New Guinea 970619113142
Date: Fri 19 Feb 1999
From: Ian Douglas douglasi@dpi.qld.gov.au

A diagnosis of Hendra virus (HeV; equine morbillivirus) in a horse has been
confirmed by the Australian Animal Health Laboratory. The diagnosis is
based on histology, immuno-peroxidase and PCR [polymerase chain reaction
testing of formalised lung tissue, and electron microscopy.
The case involves an adult, thoroughbred mare kept for polocrosse [a sport.
The mare
died early on 18 January 1999 after an illness lasting 24 hours. Clinical
signs included anorexia, depression, gait abnormality, ataxia and facial
edema. At death large quantities of froth flowed from the nostrils. This
froth was described as yellow in color. The appearance of the sclera
suggested some jaundice.
The horse was one of two kept on a 1.5 hectare paddock within the
residential area of a beachside community near Cairns. The second horse was
sampled on 8 February 1999 and has tested negative for HeV by ELISA
[enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay. Both horses occupied the paddock
continuously for the past two months with no reported horse movement onto
or away from the paddock.
Previous research has shown that HeV antibody can occur in flying foxes,
large bats of the genus _Pteropus_. The paddock contains trees that are
occasionally visited by spectacled flying foxes.
This is the first evidence of this disease in a horse since the virus was
first recognised in September 1994. In October 1995, a human case occurred
and traceback showed contact in August 1994 with two horses that were
subsequently shown to be infected. In 1995 an extensive retrospective study
of laboratory records and stored specimens did not detect any other cases.
Intensive surveillance has been maintained in Queensland since that time
and horses with suspicious signs followed up for HeV exclusion.
>From the history of these horses and the disease's epidemiological pattern
it seems clear that infection of this mare has not originated from another
horse, nor has any lateral spread occurred to other horses. It seems likely
that spread has occurred in this case from a natural host, probably a
flying fox. Such an occurrence is a very rare event, with only three known
foci of infection ever having been recorded.
--
K J Dunn
Chief Veterinary Officer (Queensland)
Animal and Plant Health Service, Department of Primary Industries
Via: Ian Douglas
Manager, Emergency Response Capability
Animal and Plant Health Service, Department of Primary Industries
